<TITLE> Canada Afghan forces lack intelligence reports </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 OTTAWA, Sept 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Canada's military mission in Afghanistan is being hampered by insufficient intelligence about enemy forces, according to an internal Defence Department report published on Wednesday. The document, extracts of which appeared in the Ottawa Citizen newspaper, said the military command running all overseas operations "clearly suffers from a lack of intelligence capability". It added: "From the command's perspective, tactical level (sub-unit and unit) commanders are not receiving the timely and actionable intelligence products." Canada has 2,500 troops in the southern city of Kandahar on a combat mission that is due to end in early 2009. So far, 70 soldiers have been killed, most by roadside bombs and mines. "In conflicts such as Afghanistan, which are widely characterized as intelligence-driven and further described as the wars of company and platoon commanders, the provision of timely and actionable tactical intelligence must be viewed as an urgent and no-fail requirement," the document said. Neither the department nor the chief spokesman for Defence Minister Peter MacKay responded to requests for comment. The Citizen said the report had been prepared in January for Gen. Rick Hillier, the chief of Canada's defense staff. Last week the officer in charge of all overseas missions told Reuters that Canadian forces had arrested several bomb makers and militants around Kandahar in the last mon
